And a trait of his that was especially worthy of admiration was this: although lavish gifts were bestowed upon him by kings, princes and nations‚ he never took anything home with him‚1 and made no change in the manner of life and dress usual with the Laconians. apt to look upon him with contempt 3 but those who knew his good qualities could not sufficiently admire him. That was his experience when, at the age of eighty, he had gone to the help of Tachos in Egypt. 361 Bc. He had taken his place at meat with his men on the shore, without any shelter and having for a couch straw spread on the ground and covered with nothing but a skin; and there too all his companions reclined beside him in plain and well-worn clothing. Their appearance, far from suggesting that there was a king among them, would indicate that they were men of no great wealth.
